{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17597765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17597765"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:28:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:28:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15429"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15429"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.24,0.43,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8120"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63350"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8120"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15429"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48801"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19692"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20711"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63350"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETumour markers are substances found in blood, urine, or body tissues that can be elevated in various types of cancer. These markers are used for screening, diagnosis, and monitoring of various cancers.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is commonly used in the diagnosis and monitoring of hepatocellular carcinoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alpha-1 antitrypsin","Alkaline phosphatase","Alpha-fetoprotein","Beta-2 microglobulin","Carcinoembryonic antigen"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EElevated levels of \u003Cstrong\u003Ealpha-fetoprotein\u003C/strong\u003E in adults can indicate hepatocellular carcinoma, with levels often exceeding 400 ng/mL. This is a glycoprotein normally produced during fetal development. It is used both diagnostically and to monitor treatment response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-1 antitrypsin\u003C/strong\u003E is a protease inhibitor that can be deficient in certain liver diseases but is not a tumour marker for hepatocellular carcinoma. \u003Cstrong\u003EAlkaline phosphatase\u003C/strong\u003E may be elevated in liver disease but is not specific for hepatocellular carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-2 microglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with multiple myeloma and lymphomas, not hepatocellular carcinoma. \u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoembryonic antigen\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used as a tumour marker for colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) is an important tumour marker for hepatocellular carcinoma and can be used for screening and monitoring.","AFP is also elevated in yolk sac tumours and during pregnancy."],"references":["Janevska D, Chaloska-Ivanova V, Janevski V. Hepatocellular Carcinoma: Risk Factors, Diagnosis and Treatment. Open Access Maced J Med Sci. 2015 Dec 15;3(4):732-6. doi: 10.3889/oamjms.2015.111. Epub 2015 Oct 29. PMID: 27275318; PMCID: PMC4877918","Asafo-Agyei KO, Samant H. Hepatocellular Carcinoma. [Updated 2023 Jun 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559177/","Balogh J, Victor D 3rd, Asham EH, Burroughs SG, Boktour M, Saharia A, Li X, Ghobrial RM, Monsour HP Jr. Hepatocellular carcinoma: a review. J Hepatocell Carcinoma. 2016 Oct 5;3:41-53. doi: 10.2147/JHC.S61146. PMID: 27785449; PMCID: PMC5063561","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48801"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15429"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48801"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T14:10:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T14:10:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8120"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63350"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta